statement.p:
Let
\omega=P\,dx+Q\,dy
be a C^1 1-form on an open set containing R. Then
\boxed{\int_{\partial R}\omega=\int_R d\omega.}
Equivalently,
\boxed{\oint_{\partial R}P\,dx+Q\,dy=\iint_R (Q_x-P_y)\,dx\wedge dy.}
Using ordinary area notation,
\boxed{\oint_{\partial R}P\,dx+Q\,dy=\iint_R (Q_x-P_y)\,dA.}

subsection.p:
This is the same theorem students usually meet as Green's theorem. The forms version
only makes the structure visible:
\omega\quad\text{lives on the boundary curve,}
while
d\omega\quad\text{lives on the plane region.}

Therefore
\boxed{\int_{\partial R}\omega=4-2=2.}
Again,
\boxed{\int_{\partial R}\omega=\int_R d\omega.}

