subsection.p:
Let R=[-1,1]\times[-1,1], and define
H(y)= \begin{cases} 0, & y\lt 0,\\ 1, & y\gt 0. \end{cases}
Consider the form \omega=H(y)\,dx. This form jumps across the line y=0, so it is not C^1 on R.

So Green's theorem becomes
\boxed{\int_{\partial R} A\,dy-B\,dx=\int_R (A_x+B_y)\,dx\wedge dy.}
In vector notation,
\boxed{\oint_{\partial R}\mathbf F\cdot\mathbf n_{\text{out}}\,ds=\iint_R \nabla\cdot\mathbf F\,dA.}
This is the two-dimensional divergence theorem.

statement.p:
Let D_a be the disk of radius a. The interior integral is \int_{D_a}2\,dx\wedge dy=2\pi a^2. Now compute the boundary flux directly. Parametrize the boundary circle counterclockwise: x=a\cos t, \qquad y=a\sin t, \qquad 0\le t\le2\pi. Then dx=-a\sin t\,dt, \qquad dy=a\cos t\,dt. So
x\,dy-y\,dx \amp= (a\cos t)(a\cos t\,dt)-(a\sin t)(-a\sin t\,dt) \amp= a^2(\cos^2t+\sin^2t)\,dt \amp= a^2\,dt.
Thus \int_{\partial D_a}\phi=\int_0^{2\pi}a^2\,dt=2\pi a^2. Again, \boxed{\int_{\partial D_a}\phi=\int_{D_a}d\phi.}
